{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538511"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16196"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.38,0.06,0.19,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8887"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66003"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8887"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5365"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43620"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66003"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her three-day-old infant for routine postnatal review. She reports difficulty with breastfeeding and is concerned about her technique. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications other than pregnancy vitamins. On examination, both mother and infant appear well with vital signs within normal limits. The infant demonstrates good tone and alertness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal tongue movement pattern during effective breastfeeding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tongue moves from posterior to anterior","Tongue moves from anterior to posterior","Uncoordinated tongue movements with intermittent suction","Stationary tongue position with vacuum creation","Vertical tongue movements against the palate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring effective breastfeeding, the infant\u0027s tongue movement follows a specific pattern that is crucial for milk extraction and transfer. \u003Cstrong\u003ETongue movement from anterior to posterior\u003C/strong\u003E in a peristaltic wave-like motion is the normal and most efficient pattern, working in conjunction with jaw movements and negative pressure to extract milk from the breast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior to anterior movement\u003C/strong\u003E would be ineffective for milk extraction and is physiologically incorrect. The tongue needs to compress the nipple against the hard palate and move posteriorly to create the necessary pressure for milk removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom tongue movements\u003C/strong\u003E would not create the coordinated pressure needed for effective milk transfer. Successful breastfeeding requires precise coordination of suckling, swallowing, and breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStationary tongue position\u003C/strong\u003E alone, even with vacuum creation, would be insufficient for effective milk removal. The peristaltic motion is essential for moving milk from the nipple to the posterior oral cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertical tongue movements\u003C/strong\u003E would not create the necessary compression and movement of milk. The tongue needs to move horizontally to strip milk from the breast effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding normal infant feeding mechanics is crucial for healthcare providers to support breastfeeding mothers. The coordinated movements of the tongue, jaw, and soft palate create a well-orchestrated system for milk removal and safe swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Effective milk removal during breastfeeding requires coordinated peristaltic tongue movements from anterior to posterior.","The let-down reflex is triggered by suckling stimulation of the nipple, not by tongue movements.","Successful breastfeeding requires coordination of suckling, swallowing, and breathing."],"references":["Scheuerle RL, Kendall RA, Tuleu C, Slater NKH, Gerrard SE. Mimicking the Impact of Infant Tongue Peristalsis on Behavior of Solid Oral Dosage Forms Administered During Breastfeeding. J Pharm Sci. 2017 Jan;106(1):193-199. doi: 10.1016/j.xphs.2016.08.006. Epub 2016 Sep 26. PMID: 27686681; PMCID: PMC5157687.","Borowitz SM. What is tongue-tie and does it interfere with breast-feeding? - a brief review. Front Pediatr. 2023 Apr 25;11:1086942. doi: 10.3389/fped.2023.1086942. PMID: 37181430; PMCID: PMC10167863.","Geddes DT, Kent JC, Mitoulas LR, Hartmann PE. Tongue movement and intra-oral vacuum in breastfeeding infants. Early Hum Dev. 2008 Jul;84(7):471-7. doi: 10.1016/j.earlhumdev.2007.12.008. Epub 2008 Feb 11. PMID: 18262736.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16196"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T17:30:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T16:02:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8887"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66003"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":